['Issue 231884: Investigate potential bug in HttpRequestHeaders::AddHeadersFromString()', 'I'm currently scanning the HTTP cache source code for something completely unrelated, and spotted the following in net/http/http_request_headers.cc:

void HttpRequestHeaders::AddHeadersFromString(
    const base::StringPiece& headers) {
  std::vector<std::string> header_line_vector;
  base::SplitStringUsingSubstr(headers.as_string(), "\r\n",
                               &header_line_vector);
  for (std::vector<std::string>::const_iterator it = header_line_vector.begin();
       it != header_line_vector.end(); ++it) {
    if (!it->empty())
      AddHeaderFromString(*it);
  }
}

The main issue is that this uses base::SplitStringUsingSubstr() to split the input string at "\r\n". Note that this function will _not_ use either '\r' or '\n' as delimiters, it will only search for the exact "\r\n" sequence and split the string there. After the split though, it trims whitespace from each token appended to the result vector.

The end result is that this doesn't deal correctly with multi-line input with embedded \n used as line separators. In other words, here's its current behaviour:

  "Foo\r\n"        -> [ "Foo" ]
  "Foo\r\nBar\r\n" -> [ "Foo", "Bar" ]
  "Foo\n"          -> [ "Foo" ]
  "Foo\nBar\n"     -> [ "Foo\nBar" ]  (!!!!)

Note that if I fix the implementation, then two HttpCache unit tests will fail (HttpCache.ConditionalizedRequestUpdatesCache9 and HttpCache.ConditionalizedRequestUpdatesCache11).

Looking at the code, it seems that's because they use the following multi-line header strings:

  const char* kExtraRequestHeaders =
      "If-Modified-Since: Wed, 06 Feb 2008 22:38:21 GMT\n"
      "If-None-Match: \"Foo2\"\n";

and

  const char* kExtraRequestHeaders =
      "If-Modified-Since: Mon, 04 Feb 2008 22:38:21 GMT\n"
      "Mon, 04 Feb 2008 22:38:21 GMT\n";

The problem is that both are interpreted as a single header line with key "If-Modified-Since", and values "Wed, 06 Feb 2008 22:38:21 GMT\nIf-None-Match: \"Foo2\"" and "Mon, 04 Feb 2008 22:38:21 GMT\nMon, 04 Feb 2008 22:38:21 GMT", respectively.

I've confirmed this by use of liberal printf()s while running the unit tests.

If I correct the strings to use \r\n line termination instead (which other unit tests already use, e.g. HttpCache.ConditionalizedRequestUpdatesCache8), then the two tests _fail_.

I suspect that this these tests are buggy, but I can't rule out at this point that this exposes a subtler bug in the HTTP cache implementation. Your input on the subject would be appreciated.

This bug it to track the issue, identify all real problems, and propose a fix.', '']

['Issue 39501: Content Scripts do not allow Conditionally Defined Functions', "Chrome Version       : 5.0.356.2 dev
Other browsers tested:
     Safari 4: FAIL
  Firefox 3.6: OK
         IE 7: ?
         IE 8: FAIL

What steps will reproduce the problem?
if( true ){
 function abc(){
  alert('abc1');
 }
}else{
 function abc(){
  alert('abc2');
 }
}
abc();//always alerts abc2 even though logically impossible

What is the expected result?
a dialog with abc1

What happens instead?
a dialog with abc2

Please provide any additional information below. Attach a screenshot if
possible.
I am assuming this has to do with some low level optimization of script.  
In firefox this type of thing is a non issue.  I enjoy quick optimization 
but it makes overriding functions or conditionally defining a different 
function for a different case or a different browser quite difficult!  I 
don't want implementation of this to slow things down, but only the last 
instance of a function is ever created, I've had to rework my content 
scripts around this fact so that the chrome function always occurs last, 
however this isn't always necessarily ideal.  

If there is a reason that allowing conditional functions would slow things 
down significantly when building the 'function table' perhaps it could be 
cached somehow depending on the site.  Perhaps functions defined in 
conditional if else or switch blocks need to be excluded or set at runtime.  
I'm running content scripts at document-start, and have a lot of time to 
decide which function to run on pageload or domready, but it's not easy to 
override unless possibly everything were stacked inside of itself.  There 
are probably other solutions by storing a huge data object but only one 
particular set would ever be applicable to the site the user is currently 
on, it would be great to skip all of the rest based on conditional logic.  

In the worst case both instances of abc() are being instantiated into 
memory and the final one is overwriting it always.  

If there were some structure or special comment to easily skip this 
function pre-compilation for a particular block that would be more than 
sufficient for me.  

//I also tested switch:
switch( 0 ){
 case 0:
 function abc(){
  alert('abc1');
 }
 break;
 case 1:
 function abc(){
  alert('abc2');
 }
}
abc(); //always abc2, same results", '']

